00:09:42.810 --> 00:09:46.080 align:middle line:90%
go within to find our answers.

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:48.640 align:middle line:84%
Starting in the
early 20th century,

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:51.480 align:middle line:84%
scientists have been
studying ice core samples

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:56.580 align:middle line:84%
from the polar regions of
the planet from 1989 to 1995.

00:09:56.580 --> 00:09:59.850 align:middle line:84%
The Greenland Ice Core
Project conducted experiments

00:09:59.850 --> 00:10:01.770 align:middle line:84%
to understand the
climate patterns

00:10:01.770 --> 00:10:06.900 align:middle line:84%
in that area for approximately
the past 100,000 years.

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:10.440 align:middle line:84%
Again, in 1998, the
collaborative ice drilling

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:14.310 align:middle line:84%
project at the Russian Vostok
station in East Antarctica

00:10:14.310 --> 00:10:16.890 align:middle line:84%
uncovered the
deepest ice core ever

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:20.070 align:middle line:84%
recorded revealing climate
data for approximately

00:10:20.070 --> 00:10:23.670 align:middle line:90%
the past 420,000 years.

00:10:23.670 --> 00:10:28.200 align:middle line:84%
Then in 2017, an ice core
taken from the blue ice

00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:30.600 align:middle line:84%
field in the Allen
Hills of Antarctica

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:36.420 align:middle line:84%
revealed ice dating to
roughly 2.7 million years old.

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:40.230 align:middle line:84%
These studies provide geologists
with a clear understanding

00:10:40.230 --> 00:10:42.970 align:middle line:84%
of the cyclical nature of
Earth's climate and weather

00:10:42.970 --> 00:10:43.770 align:middle line:90%
patterns.

00:10:43.770 --> 00:10:47.220 align:middle line:84%
Geologists refer to the
past and current epics

00:10:47.220 --> 00:10:51.970 align:middle line:84%
as the Pleistocene
and the Holocene.

00:10:51.970 --> 00:10:56.030 align:middle line:84%
>> The Pleistocene epic began
about 2.8 million years ago.

00:10:56.030 --> 00:10:58.900 align:middle line:84%
And this is the sheets
of ice that we often

00:10:58.900 --> 00:11:02.260 align:middle line:84%
talk about covered North
America, the Greenland Northern

00:11:02.260 --> 00:11:03.490 align:middle line:90%
Europe.

00:11:03.490 --> 00:11:08.800 align:middle line:84%
That period, that epic,
ended about 11,500 years ago

00:11:08.800 --> 00:11:11.710 align:middle line:84%
as we began the current
epic that we're in now

00:11:11.710 --> 00:11:13.720 align:middle line:90%
which is called the Holocene.

00:11:13.720 --> 00:11:17.900 align:middle line:84%
However, when we go from
one epic to another,

00:11:17.900 --> 00:11:20.650 align:middle line:84%
it's not a clean break,
there's a transition period.

00:11:20.650 --> 00:11:23.320 align:middle line:84%
There's a buffer between
the two and that buffer

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:26.650 align:middle line:84%
is the mystery that helps us
to understand what happened

00:11:26.650 --> 00:11:29.320 align:middle line:90%
in these ancient civilizations.

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:35.410 align:middle line:10%
Between 12,800 years ago
and 11,600 years ago,

00:11:35.410 --> 00:11:39.430 align:middle line:10%
that little window of time is
an extraordinary period of time

00:11:39.430 --> 00:11:42.220 align:middle line:10%
that geologists call
the Younger Dryas.

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:45.100 align:middle line:10%
There are plant species
that only exist in cold.

00:11:45.100 --> 00:11:47.200 align:middle line:10%
One of those plants
is called the Dryas,

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:50.680 align:middle line:10%
and this is where the term
the Younger Dryas comes from.

00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:53.770 align:middle line:84%
There is evidence
of the Younger Dryas

00:11:53.770 --> 00:11:57.700 align:middle line:84%
far down into North America
and down into Northern Europe

00:11:57.700 --> 00:12:00.790 align:middle line:84%
suggesting that these
were cold temperatures

00:12:00.790 --> 00:12:02.510 align:middle line:90%
during this period of time.

00:12:02.510 --> 00:12:04.210 align:middle line:84%
And when the temperatures
began to warm,

00:12:04.210 --> 00:12:07.390 align:middle line:84%
